South Africa’s unemployment rate has decreased by 0.4 percentage points from 27.5% in the third quarter in 2018 to 27.1% at the end of the year. This is according to the Quarterly Labour Force Survey released by Statistics South Africa (StatsSA) on Tuesday. These surveys are conducted every three months and measure changes in the labour force from quarter to quarter and over longer periods of time. According to the Stats SA, there are 38.1-million people of working age (15-64) in the country and of this number, 16.5-million are employed, 6.1-million are unemployed and 12.6 million are not economically active due to a variety of reasons including being discouraged by seeking for jobs to no avail.
